== History == [[File:Yushima Seido6.jpg|thumb|The "Taiseiden" (Confucius Shrine) at Yushima Seido (February 3, 2010)]] {{See also|Yushima Seido}} === As the Hayashi Family's Private Academy === In {{ill|1605|ja|1605th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1605|qq=}} (Keichō 10), {{ill|Hayashi Razan|ja|林羅山|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/Hayashi Razan|qq=}} entered the service of Tokugawa Ieyasu as a Buddhist scholar. By {{ill|1630|ja|1630th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1630|qq=}} (Kan'ei 7), Tokugawa Iemitsu granted the Hayashi family land in Ueno for a school. This was the foundation of what would later become the Shōheizaka Academy.
=== Establishment of the Gakumonjo === In {{ill|1790|ja|1790th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1790|qq=}} (Kansei 2), as part of the "Kansei Edict on Neo-Confucianism" (寛政異学の禁), the institution was reorganized into a government-operated academy.
=== Transition to "Shōhei School" === During the Meiji Restoration, the academy was briefly rebranded as the "Shōhei School" but was eventually dissolved in {{ill|1870|ja|1870th year|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/1870|qq=}} (Meiji 3). It had limited influence on the formation of the modern {{ill|University of Tokyo|ja|東京大学|qq=draft|qq=draft|12=simple|13=User:Immanuelle/University of Tokyo|qq=}}.
